muKern - Hardening Interlude (Phase 5.5)
========================================

Before the Phase 6 ports, we pay down the security/robustness debt accumulated
while standing up the user-space servers. Each item below is a milestone landed
as its own bisectable commit that builds and boots in QEMU, verified with the
same format-patch -> git am -> boot loop used in Phases 2-5. The kernel stays
mechanism-only and under 5,000 lines; everything else is policy in servers/.

ADDRESSED IN THIS PATCH
-----------------------

H1: Capability-gated hardware I/O
    Port I/O was unrestricted (any Ring 3 thread could SYS_OUTB to any port).
    Add a CAP_IOPORT capability carrying an allowed [base,len) port range.
    SYS_OUTB/SYS_INB/SYS_INW now require the caller to hold a covering cap.
    init (the root task, tid 0) is the only thread permitted to grant ranges
    (SYS_GRANT_IO); it hands the UART to the console driver and the ATA ports
    to the block driver during their startup handshake. A thread without the
    capability is denied.

H2: Pager policy + fault isolation (+ slot reclamation)
    The pager mapped *any* faulting address (a zero-page-on-demand oracle).
    It now validates the address against a registered region; an out-of-bounds
    fault is a policy decision to KILL the offending process. The kernel kills
    on the pager's verdict (returned with the fault reply), the faulting thread
    is torn down, and the rest of the system keeps running - demonstrating
    fault isolation. Dead thread slots are reclaimed so tids/stacks are reused.

DEFERRED (sketched for Phase 6+)
--------------------------------

H3: Per-process address spaces. A private PML4 per process; switch CR3 on
    context switch and on cross-space IPC. This is the big one: it breaks the
    current shared-address-space shortcut where servers read each other's
    buffers by raw pointer, so it must land together with H4. Its own phase.

H4: Zero-copy shared memory by grant. Replace raw pointer passing with explicit
    shared regions delegated through a memory capability in the IPC message
    (the DESIGN's "map a shared buffer via a capability" path). Prerequisite
    for H3 so drivers/FS can still move bulk data without a private-AS copy.

H5: Interrupt forwarding. Drivers currently poll. Add the DESIGN's mechanism:
    a driver registers for an IRQ, the kernel masks it and forwards each
    interrupt as an IPC to the driver thread, which acks to re-unmask. Converts
    the console/block drivers to interrupt-driven and enables input devices.

H6: Name service. Replace the well-known-tid-by-spawn-order convention with a
    registry server: servers register a name, clients look it up. Removes the
    fragile fixed boot ordering.

H7: Filesystem maturity. Directories, multiple files, partial/seeked reads,
    writes, and a block cache in fs_server (still no kernel involvement).

H8: Full resource accounting. Per-process frame ownership tracked at map time
    and reclaimed on exit/kill. Depends on H3's private address spaces.

This ordering front-loads the cheap, high-value isolation wins (H1/H2) and
groups the expensive, entangled work (H3/H4/H8) so it can be done coherently.
